    {
      q: 'How is a bridge different from an implant?',
      a: 'A bridge spans the gap using adjacent teeth as anchors — those teeth must be prepared (ground down) to support crowns. An implant replaces the root itself, stands independently, and requires no modification of neighboring teeth. Implants are generally the superior long-term solution, but bridges are appropriate when adjacent teeth already need crowns or bone levels aren\'t ideal for implants.',
    },
    {
      q: 'How many visits does a bridge take?',
      a: 'A traditional bridge typically requires two visits. At the first, we prepare the anchor teeth, take digital impressions, and place temporaries. The permanent bridge is cemented at the second visit, 2–3 weeks later.',
    },
    {
